                    <callout1 type="arabic">UNDER SEAT HEATER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Driver Heater and Control</title>
            <figure id="f47005212" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g47005212.webp" filename="../figg47/G47005212.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                         scalefitwidth="272px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 212. Driver Heater</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER SUPPLY LINE TO AUXILIARY HEATERS</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">DRIVER HEATER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">AUXILIARY HEATER RETURNS</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">WHEEL WELL COVER</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <para>The driver heater is located along the floor line below the driver left wing switch panel. The heater
                controls for the driver heater are located on the driver left wing switch panel.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Maintenance</title>
            <para>It is recommended that the heating system be inspected annually. However, more critical areas, such as
                around the engine, should be inspected on a regular basis. Filters should be removed and cleaned
                regularly.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Heaters and Accessories</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">Heater Coils</emph>
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">The heater coils are most efficient when the coils, fins and air flow passages are
                        kept clean and free of dirt and dust. The coils should be cleaned with a soft flow compressed
                        dry air or vacuum and a soft brush. Damaged fins should be straightened to prevent air flow
                        restrictions.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">Hoses</emph>
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">All heater hoses should be inspected for kinks and chafing that will cause failure.
                        Hoses should be replaced when cracks or permanent distortions are found.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Hoses and clamps should be checked regularly. Hoses may appear in good condition on
                        the outside, but the inside may be partially deteriorated. If there are any doubts about the
                        condition of the hoses, replacements should be made. Clamps should be inspected to ensure they
                        are strong enough to hold a tight connection.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">Motors/Switches/Blowers and Fans</emph>
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Motors are essentially maintenance free and do not require any lubrication or
                        cleaning. However, excessive vibration caused by damaged blowers, wheels, and fans can cause
                        motor damage.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Switches are maintenance free, but can be damaged by water and loose wire
                        connections. Loose wires cause the component to require more amperage than normal. Inspect on a
                        regular basis.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Defroster fans can be mounted on the bulkhead above the driver. The fans should be
                        kept clean of dirt and dust. The metal cage can be removed for blade cleaning. Bend the metal
                        lock clamps to remove the metal cage.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">Antifreeze</emph>
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">The antifreeze mixture of the coolant system is a 50/50 mixture of antifreeze and
                        water. The mixture will protect the unit to -40 degrees F. For added protection in colder
                        climates, refer to the engine coolant section.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Troubleshooting</title>
            <para>Typically when a school bus does not have heat or air flow, several steps should be taken to eliminate
                the problem. Use the steps below as a guide to problem solving.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Use the following procedure to remove the pressure-type cap from the radiator. Always allow
                        the engine to cool first. Wrap a thick, heavy cloth around the cap. Push down, loosen cap slowly
                        to the first notch position; then pause a moment. This will avoid possible scalding by hot steam
                        or water, which can result in injury and/or property damage.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">No Heat from the Engine</emph>
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Check the heater hose gate valves. Make sure they are open (supply and return).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f47005213" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g47005213.webp" filename="../figg47/G47005213.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                                 scalefitwidth="272px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 213. Heater Hose Gate Valves</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Check the coolant level. Make sure the coolant system is full and flowing.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Touch the heater hoses and feel for heat at the engine supply hose.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Inspect the heater hose routing for kinked hose that could block coolant flow.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Make sure the booster pump is operating correctly if present.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Open the bleeder valve and check for air in the heater hose (air lock).</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Check engine operating temperature gauge and compare to air flow from heaters.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Check the butterfly valve and actuating cable for proper operation.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">No Air Flow from Heater Vents or Ducts</emph>
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Check the circuit breaker or fuse.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Check the switch.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Check the blower motor.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Check the resistor.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Check the harness connections for an open circuit.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Repair any items that are not functioning as required.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Heater / Defroster and Blower Motor Access Procedures</title>
            <para>Each blower assembly has a resistor that controls the speed of the rotor. The defroster / step switch
                is a three-speed switch with a three-post resistor. When checking for speed variation, check all three
                speeds. Use a multi-meter to check the resistor. Refer to the IC Bus Troubleshooting Guide.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Access Main Front Heater / Defroster Blower Motors and Resistors Assembly</title>
            <para>To access the driver / main heater assemblies use the following steps:</para>
            <figure id="f47005214" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g47005214.webp" filename="../figg47/G47005214.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                         scalefitwidth="272px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 214. Access Main Front Heater</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">MAIN HEATER COIL ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">MAIN HEATER COVER PLATE</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">COVER PLATE MOUNTING SCREWS</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">HEATED ASSEMBLY BODY</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">Driver Heater Filter</emph>
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove all surface mounting screws.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove lower return screws.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove driver's foot warm duct.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove mounting screws for driver left switch panel and storage compartment.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Lift panel away from heater assembly.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Auxiliary / Midship Heater Motor Access</title>
            <para>To gain access the auxiliary heater motor or resistors, use the following steps.</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The auxiliary and/or midship heaters may vary in location. The rear auxiliary heaters
                    when used with the wheel chair access door may be a vertically wall mounted assembly. The under seat
                    heaters will be mounted under the standard passenger seat assembly. Depending on the type service
                    the seat may or may not require removal.
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Locate the passenger seat above the heater assembly.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Flip the seat cushion up by adjusting the seat clip.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove the heater cover panel mounting screws in the center.</para>
                    <figure id="f47005215" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g47005215.webp" filename="../figg47/G47005215.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                                 scalefitwidth="272px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 215. Under Seat Heater Access</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">UNDER SEAT HEATER ASSEMBLY TOP COVER PLATE</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">UNDER SEAT HEATER ASSEMBLY BODY</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">UNDER SEAT HEATER LOWER COVER PLATE</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER MOTOR HARNESS CONNECTION</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove the screws that secure the heater to the floor.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Pull the heater panels apart, exposing the internal parts.</para>
                    <figure id="f47005216" figsize="pg-wide">
                        <graphic id="g47005216" filename="../figg47/G47005216.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                                 scalefitwidth="392px" scalefitheight="392px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 216. Under Seat Heater Core Removal</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER CORE</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">CORE MOUNTING SCREWS</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">UNDER SEAT HEATER BODY ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">BLOWER FAN</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">BLOWER MOTOR MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">BLOWER MOTOR</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">RHEOSTATS</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER BOTTOM COVER</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER HARNESS CONNECTIONS</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Locate the heater motor and disconnect the wire leads from the resistor.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove the motor casing nuts that secure the motor to the shroud.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove the fan from the motor shaft by using a small Allen wrench and turning the
                        set screw counter-clockwise.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Step Well Heater Assembly</title>
            <para>To access the step well heater assembly, check for optional components that may be existing and have
                to be removed to gain access to the step well heater.
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">Filter Remove</emph>
                </para>
                <para>To remove, clean or change step well heater filter use the following procedure:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Locate the 3 filter plate mounting screws.</para>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Loosen and remove mounting screws.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Remove the filter cover plate.</para>
                        <figure id="f47005217" figsize="col-wide">
                            <graphic id="g47005217.webp" filename="../figg47/G47005217.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                                     scalefitwidth="272px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                            <caption>Figure 217. Filter Remove</caption>
                            <calloutgroup>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER FILTER</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER FRONT COVER PLATE</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">FILTER ACCESS COVER MOUNTING SCREWS</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">FILTER ACCESS COVER</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER BODY ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            </calloutgroup>
                        </figure>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Remove the filter assembly.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>To install filter, reverse Steps 1 through 3.</para>
                    </step3>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">Remove Step Well Heater Blower Assembly</emph>
                    </para>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Remove the optional assist handrail (if applicable).</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Remove the fire extinguisher and mounting bracket (if applicable)</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Remove the mounting screws along the lower edge of passenger entry dash panel.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Loosen and remove the mounting screws on face plate (cover weldment).</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Loosen and remove the defroster hose clamps attaching defroster hose to front face
                            plate.
                        </para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Disconnect the harness plug connection to dual wheel blower assembly (if blower is to be
                            removed).
                        </para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Loosen and remove the five dual wheel blower mounting screws attaching the blower assembly
                            to the case weldment. Remove the dual wheel blower assembly.
                        </para>
                        <figure id="f47005218" figsize="pg-wide">
                            <graphic id="g47005218.webp" filename="../figg47/G47005218.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                                     scalefitwidth="312px" scalefitheight="312px"/>
                            <caption>Figure 218. Heater Coil and Blower Removal</caption>
                            <calloutgroup>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">URETHANE INSULATOR</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER CORE</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER ASSEMBLY BODY</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER RHEOSTAT SWITCH</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">BLOWER FAN ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">BLOWER MOTOR HARNESS CONNECTIONS</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">BLOWER MOTOR MOUNTING SCREWS</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER CORE ACCESS PLATE MOUNTING SCREWS</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER CORE ACCESS PLATE</callout1>
                                <callout1 type="arabic">HEATER CORE MOUNTING SCREWS</callout1>
                            </calloutgroup>
                        </figure>
                    </step3>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">Heater Coil Removal</emph>
                    </para>
                    <para>The supply lines to and from the step well heater coil should be closed, prior to removal
                        procedure.
                    </para>
                    <para>Follow the procedures above to access the heater coil. To remove the heater coil:</para>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Locate the four mounting screws on the coil assembly bracket. Loosen and remove the
                            mounting screws.
                        </para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Partially remove the heater coil assembly to gain access to the hose clamp connection to
                            the supply and return lines.
                        </para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Remove the coil gasket.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Remove the heater coil.</para>
                    </step3>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
